<subSubSection pageId="110" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="110" pageNumber="111">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephaloleia donckieri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="donckieri">Cephaloleia donckieri</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephaloleia elaeidis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elaeidis">Cephaloleia elaeidis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephaloleia tarsata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsata">Cephaloleia tarsata</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Cephaloleia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephaloleia zikani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zikani">Cephaloleia zikani</taxonomicName>
. It can be distinguished by the vertex of the head without a medial fovea, by the serrulate lateral margins of the pronotum, by the smooth apical margins of the elytra, and by antennomere 2 being obconic.
</paragraph>
